etymologies: late 16th century (in an earlier sense). Partly from classical Latin reductus, past participle of reducere reduce, and partly from post-classical Latin reductus refuge, hiding place, retreat

definitions: A mathematical or logical structure derived from a given structure by disregarding some of the operations and relations of the latter.

etymologies: mid 16th century (in an earlier sense). From classical Latin redūct-, past participial stem of redūcere reduce; compare earlier reduct and also later reduct

definitions: To deduct (a sum or amount). Also without object. Chiefly US, regional in later use.
To bring down or diminish in size, number, amount, or degree.
